male:
Additional information
            APPOINTMENTS To book an appointment please use our online booking service (https://patient.emisaccess.co.uk), phone reception or visit the surgery between our normal working hours of 8am and 6.30pm Monday to Friday. We offer a mixture of appointments available on the day and appointments that can be booked in advance. We do offer our patients the opportunity to pre book an appointment from 7.30am on Tuesday and Thursday, until 7pm Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, and between the hours of 8.00am and 9.30am on a Saturday morning. We would respectfully ask patients that can attend the surgery during the day for routine treatment to do so. By doing this you will help those patients who need to see a GP for routine care but have difficulty coming to the surgery during our normal working hours. Before 8am and after 6.30pm Monday to Friday and on a Saturday morning we will not be able to see you for any problem that requires urgent attention. You will need to ring the out of hours service. The easiest way to access the out of hours service is to ring the surgery and your call will be diverted. The GP appointments offered outside our normal working hours are only for routine care. If you attend the surgery during the extended hours time periods and do not have a pre-booked appointment we will not be able to see you. The telephone lines will be answered by the practice from 8.00am to 6.30pm Monday to Friday. Outside of these times your call will be diverted to the out of hours service. A receptionist will be available in reception from 8am to 6.30pm Monday to Friday. During these hours they will be able to assist with appointment booking and the ordering of prescriptions. If You No Longer Require Your Appointment If you are unable to attend your appointment please ring us on 0117 9591919 and cancel as soon as possible so that your appointment can be used by someone else. Telephone Advice If you wish to speak to a doctor please telephone the practice on 0117 9591919. The receptionist will ask you for a short message and your telephone number. The doctor will call you back. Home Visits If you are too unwell to come to the surgery, please telephone your visit request BEFORE 10.30am as the doctor’s plan their rounds at that time. The doctor may telephone you first to discuss your problem. You may be seen sooner if you can be brought to the surgery. Out Of Hours Calls If you or a member of your family are in need of urgent medical advice or treatment please contact the duty doctor by telephoning the Surgery on 0117 9591919.

male:
Additional information
            Message from Dr. Coppock
 “The demands on the Health Service are increasing, especially on the Accident and Emergency Department.  Please remember that the Accident and Emergency Department as it says is for accidents and emergencies.  By going there when you haven’t had an accident or when it is not an emergency you will clog up the system and prevent doctors and nurses there from dealing with genuine accidents and emergencies.  Apart from this the doctors in the Accident and Emergency Department are designed to deal with accidents and emergencies not with chronic diseases or minor ailments so by attending the Accident and Emergency Department with these problems you will not be getting the best or appropriate treatment.  Please bare this in mind.” For medical problems outside our opening hours please phone 111 and you will be directed to the appropriate service.

accepting: We are currently accepting new patients
male:
Additional information
            APPOINTMENTS To book an appointment please use our online booking service (https://patient.emisaccess.co.uk), phone reception or visit the surgery between our normal working hours of 8am and 6.30pm Monday to Friday. We offer a mixture of appointments available on the day and appointments that can be booked in advance. We do offer our patients the opportunity to pre book an appointment from 7.30am on Tuesday and Thursday, until 7pm Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, and between the hours of 8.00am and 9.30am on a Saturday morning. We would respectfully ask patients that can attend the surgery during the day for routine treatment to do so. By doing this you will help those patients who need to see a GP for routine care but have difficulty coming to the surgery during our normal working hours. Before 8am and after 6.30pm Monday to Friday and on a Saturday morning we will not be able to see you for any problem that requires urgent attention. You will need to ring the out of hours service. The easiest way to access the out of hours service is to ring the surgery and your call will be diverted. The GP appointments offered outside our normal working hours are only for routine care. If you attend the surgery during the extended hours time periods and do not have a pre-booked appointment we will not be able to see you. The telephone lines will be answered by the practice from 8.00am to 6.30pm Monday to Friday. Outside of these times your call will be diverted to the out of hours service. A receptionist will be available in reception from 8am to 6.30pm Monday to Friday. During these hours they will be able to assist with appointment booking and the ordering of prescriptions. If You No Longer Require Your Appointment If you are unable to attend your appointment please ring us on 0117 9591919 and cancel as soon as possible so that your appointment can be used by someone else. Telephone Advice If you wish to speak to a doctor please telephone the practice on 0117 9591919. The receptionist will ask you for a short message and your telephone number. The doctor will call you back. Home Visits If you are too unwell to come to the surgery, please telephone your visit request BEFORE 10.30am as the doctor’s plan their rounds at that time. The doctor may telephone you first to discuss your problem. You may be seen sooner if you can be brought to the surgery. Out Of Hours Calls If you or a member of your family are in need of urgent medical advice or treatment please contact the duty doctor by telephoning the Surgery on 0117 9591919.

male:
Additional information
            Appointments are put on the system every Friday afternoon for a two week period.  Each day there will be thee pre bookable appointments in the morning and the afternoon.  There are also three EMIS Access Appointments for each surgery at the beginning and end of each consultation for each GP.  If you would like to sign up for EMIS Access so that you can book your appointments "On Line" then please ask the Receptionist at your normal surgery for a Form for EMIS Access to Register.  All other appointments are "Book on the Day".

If you are being specific as to which GP you want to see then you may have to wait a couple of days to see that particular GP.  

If there are no appointnments available on the day you should ask for a Telephone Consultation.  The Receptionist will Triage all calls coming in to the surgery and ask you for a few details and your contact telephone number.  You will be channelled through to the appropriate Health Care Professional who will be able to help you.  The Health Care Professional  will ring you during the morning or afternoon surgery and if the Health Care Professional thinks that it is necessary , you will be asked to attend  the surgery for a consultation but you may have to wait a while to be seen.

            We now offer pre-bookable appointments for Monday and Thursday evening surgeries, between 6.30 p.m. to 8.00 p.m. This service is for patients who are unable to attend during normal surgery hours. Also we now open one Saturday per month for prebooked appointments only.

This service is not a Walk in service or emergency surgery- Patients, who require emergency consultations during these surgeries, must use the Walk in Centre at Ashford Hospital.  Children under the age of two years  must attend St. Peters Hospital, Chertsey. If you need to see a doctor outside our normal surgery hours, out of Hours cover is provided by Thamesdoc on 02083909991.  Alternatively you may obtain free expert advice form NHS direct on 0845 4647.  

Patients who attend the surgery in anticipation of being seen by a doctor without an appointment will be directed to an appropriate service such as the Walk in Centre at Ashford or Accident and Emergency Department.

For security reasons, the surgery will operate a locked door service; entry will only be to patients who have a pre booked appointment

The Practice telephone system will remain diverted after 6.00 p.m.  to the answer phone which will provide details of our Out of Hours service.

male:
Additional information
            APPOINTMENTS To book an appointment please use our online booking service (https://patient.emisaccess.co.uk), phone reception or visit the surgery between our normal working hours of 8am and 6.30pm Monday to Friday. We offer a mixture of appointments available on the day and appointments that can be booked in advance. We do offer our patients the opportunity to pre book an appointment from 7.30am on Tuesday and Thursday, until 7pm Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, and between the hours of 8.00am and 9.30am on a Saturday morning. We would respectfully ask patients that can attend the surgery during the day for routine treatment to do so. By doing this you will help those patients who need to see a GP for routine care but have difficulty coming to the surgery during our normal working hours. Before 8am and after 6.30pm Monday to Friday and on a Saturday morning we will not be able to see you for any problem that requires urgent attention. You will need to ring the out of hours service. The easiest way to access the out of hours service is to ring the surgery and your call will be diverted. The GP appointments offered outside our normal working hours are only for routine care. If you attend the surgery during the extended hours time periods and do not have a pre-booked appointment we will not be able to see you. The telephone lines will be answered by the practice from 8.00am to 6.30pm Monday to Friday. Outside of these times your call will be diverted to the out of hours service. A receptionist will be available in reception from 8am to 6.30pm Monday to Friday. During these hours they will be able to assist with appointment booking and the ordering of prescriptions. If You No Longer Require Your Appointment If you are unable to attend your appointment please ring us on 0117 9591919 and cancel as soon as possible so that your appointment can be used by someone else. Telephone Advice If you wish to speak to a doctor please telephone the practice on 0117 9591919. The receptionist will ask you for a short message and your telephone number. The doctor will call you back. Home Visits If you are too unwell to come to the surgery, please telephone your visit request BEFORE 10.30am as the doctor’s plan their rounds at that time. The doctor may telephone you first to discuss your problem. You may be seen sooner if you can be brought to the surgery. Out Of Hours Calls If you or a member of your family are in need of urgent medical advice or treatment please contact the duty doctor by telephoning the Surgery on 0117 9591919.

Telephone triage and telephone consultation:
To ease the winter pressure the Practice is offering a telephone triage and telephone consultations every Monday between January and March 2014.

If you feel unwell and require a telephone consultation please telephone the surgery on Monday morning between 9am and 10am on 020 8332 7515. The receptionist or Health Care Assistant will ask you a few questions to assess your condition. According to your clinical needs, you will either be given an appointment or a telephone consultation with a GP.

If you were booked for a telephone consultation, the GP will call you back between 11am and 12pm and will offer you advice for your clinical condition.

Additional information
            Our reception is open 8:00am - 6:30pm Every weekday, We run extended access clinics until 8:00pm on Mondays and Tuesdays for pre booked appointments only. 

To book an appointment:

The patient telephones the surgery and leaves their name, contact number and a brief description of their symptoms.

Patient will be offered a telephone consultation with the GP of their choice, where possible.

The doctor will then call the patient to discuss their condition. The doctor will then either make an appointment for the patient to come to see them on the same day or give advice and treatment over the telephone, as appropriate.

We will have a limited number of face-to-face afternoon appointments available for returns that have been requested by a doctor.
Why does my practice close some Wednesdays?

Keeping up to date with new treatments and techniques is really important in the NHS. Once a month on a Wednesday morning - our GPs go to training events to help make sure that you are getting the very best care possible.

On these days you can still be seen by our out of hours service during this time.  If you need to see a Dr before our Surgery is open again call 0330 100 4471.

Here are the dates and times we will be closed this year:

•13th December, 2017 from 8:30am-1pm

For Emergency appointment please call or walk in 08:30- 09:30, These appointments are first come first serve basis.

You don't need face to face consultation for sick note, letter for  Social services, referral query, medication query, results etc. You can book telephone consultation with a GP.

Additional information
            Aditional Capacity and Extended Hours appointments can be obtained at local GP surgeries by phoning 020 7540 9949 / 020 7511 2075.  Appointments are available Monday to Fridays evenings and Saturday mornings.

Online booking appointments and prescription ordering is available. Please speak to a member of staff.

Please cancel your appointments if you are not able to attend at the surgery, hospital or any other NHS organisations, so that those appointments can be given to other patients.

To book an appointment for the next working day, you may call at 10:00am, due to the increased calls at 10am mon-fri please call in the afternoon for any other queries.  

We have a walk-in clinic that starts at 9:00am daily mon-fri, it is on first come first seen basis unitl all the available appointments are taken, after this time you will be advised on all other options of booking an appointment.

We offer advance appointments, that can be booked at any time, please note these are limited.  

We also have working patients appointments.  

There are times when the walk-in-clinic is not busy, therefore we ask that you call around 09:15-9:45am, and depending on the demand on the day, if there are appointments available, we will ask you to come that morning.

CHAPERONE GUIDELINES
We are committed to provide safe, comfortable environment for patients and staff. All patients are entitled to have a chaperone present for any consultation, examination or procedure where they feel one is required. This chaperone my be a family member or friend. On occasions you may prefer a formal chaperone to be present i.e. a trained member of staff. Please enquire at reception if you need one.


FREE NHS HEALTH CHECK
You may be entitled to a free NHS Health Check - Please ask at reception for details.

SHINGLES VACCINATION
If you are aged 70, 78 or 79 on or after 1/9/2014 you are eligable for the Shingles Vaccine. PLEASE BOOK AN APPOINTMENT AT THE SURGERY YOU ATTEND.  PATIENTS WHO FAIL TO ATTEND FOR BOOKED APPOINTMENTS.
Our practice has a high number of DNA appointments. From our last practice participation group meeting it was agreed that DNA appointment should be one of or practice priorities to be addressed. We are suggesting that patients who fail to attend three appointments or more and have not made contact with the practice will be removed from our practice list. Please note vulnerable patients will not be removed from the practice list. 
The practice would like to invite patients to make comment or suggestions to our proposal to address the practice problem of patients who fail to attend appointments which impacts on others to book appointments.

male:
Additional information
            We are open every alternate Saturday between 9-12PM                                                                                                                                         /The GP surgery is based in Church Elm Lane Health Centre which also houses other community services like Phlebotomy, Health Visitors, District Nurses and Talking Therapies which are NOT part of the GP. Please contact 0300 300 1790 to access these services.                                                                                                                      PLEASE NOTE: Medical Practice is closed for lunch between 1-2pm. The lunchtime break allows reception to handover between morning and afternoon sessions. This period needs to be uninterrupted so that there can be a safe and efficient handover.                                                                                                                                     A doctor's working day comprises of administration as well as seeing patients. The administration component of being a GP has increased considerably over the years and can sometimes take upto 50% of the working day. During the break in between surgeries, the doctor will read and action hospital letters, complete referrals and tasks from the surgery, answer queries, check blood test results, issue medications, conduct home visits and deal with any emergencies.       There are also regular meetings with district nurses, community matrons and social workers to discuss complex cases. In addition, the doctors and nurses have a responsibility to complete frequent audits to ensure care and quality is maintained. Furthermore, practice meetings also take place to discuss any issues or improvement projects within the practice. Educational meetings allow doctors and nurses to keep our skills and knowledge upto date. All of these tasks ensure that the practice runs as efficiently and safely as possible.

Please telephone us before 10.00am:  The doctor does the visit rounds at lunch time between surgeries.  Please visit the surgery if you are able:  The Surgery is fully equipped to facilitate your care.  In the time taken to visit a patient at home four patients emergencies can be treated in the surgery.
The doctor may arrange for your visit to be by the comunity treatment team if that is most appropriate.

accepting: We are currently accepting new patients
male:
Additional information
            We run eight "never-full" surgeries every week.  These are at 1130 every morning and 1700 on the evenings we have an afternoon surgery.  If you want to be seen that day and there are no appointments left in the normal surgeries you will be offered an appointment in the "never-full" surgery and told how many other patients are already booked to be seen that day.  We see patients in the order they book and not when they arrive so coming early does not mean you will be seen sooner and other patients arriving later may be seen before you.    The GP doing these surgeries will be the duty GP for that day.  If you particularly want to see one of the three GPs or you are following up a problem it is best to plan ahead and book with the doctor you want or the one who has been seeing you.  We encourage patients to avoid flitting between GPs to get different opinions.   These "never-full" appointments are best for problems that have recently arisen and you want to get immediate care.  We will see everyone who books but routine review appointments that can be booked weeks ahead are best seen in the normal surgeries by your usual GP.

We keep a small number of appointments free at the start of every surgery so patients  becoming ill overnight can be seen at the start of the day.  If you have a problem that may need a test sent to the hospital (almost all infections) please tell the receptionist and  come in the morning. We may see you quickly between other patients before the courier collects our samples at 1130.  In general we do not treat infections until we have a hospital report confirming the diagnosis and the need (or not) for antibiotics. 

If you need a home visit please ring as early as possible.  The GP will usually ring you soon after the request to start your care.

You can speak to a GP on the telephone and good times to do this are before the surgery starts between 0800 and 0830 and after the surgery has ended around 12 noon and 1730.  On Tuesdays the GP will ring you back once she has finished seeing patients and this may be in the afternoon.  If you ring during the surgery the call will not be put through to the GP if they are with another patient and you will be given a time to ring back when the GP is more likely to be free to take the call.   Emergency calls (like a collapse) will always interupt the GP. 

On Tuesday between 1200 and 1830 the surgery is covered by Fovant Surgery and calls are automatically redirected.  On Thursday evening between 1700 and 1830 calls are redirected to a Hindon Surgery GP mobile telephone.  This is to answer emergency calls and is not a suitable time to ring for routine matters like booking appointments or getting test results. In the past two years  almost every call was to book an appointment or some other routine matter.

The extended hours surgeries (18:30 - 19:00) do not operate on some evenings during leave periods.  They are intended for working patients who have difficulty coming at other times. 

When we are open all the usual nursing and dispensary services are also available except during the extended hours surgeries and the annual Saturday morning 'flu clinics in October.

Please allow 48 hours for prescription requests to be fulfilled.

Additional information
            ALL APPOINTMENTS ARE AVAILABLE TO BOOK UP TO 4 WEEKS IN ADVANCE.  YOU HAVE THE RIGHT TO REQUEST TO SEE A SPECIFIC DOCTOR, ALTHOUGH DUE TO HOLIDAYS OR PART TIME WORKING WE MAY NOT BE ABLE TO GIVE YOU AN APPOINTMENT WITH A SPECIFIC DOCTOR IN THE REQUIRED OR CONVENIENT TIMESCALE TO YOU, THEREFORE YOU WILL ALWAYS BE OFFERED THE CHOICE TO SEE A DIFFERENT DOCTOR WHICH MAY BE MORE APPROPRIATE TO YOUR REQUIREMENTS.

WE RUN A TRIAGE SYSTEM IF YOU WISH TO SEE A GP ON THE DAY. WE WILL TAKE BRIEF DETAILS OF YOUR SYMPTOMS AND A CONTACT TELEPHONE NUMBER SO THAT THE TRIAGE DOCTOR CAN RING YOU BACK IN THE MORNING OR AFTERNOON. IF YOU DO NOT WISH TO STATE THE REASON FOR YOUR APPOINTMENT REQUEST YOU CAN SIMPLY TELL THE RECEPTIONIST THAT IT IS A PERSONAL MATTER. RECEPTION STAFF SIGN CONFIDENTIALITY AGREEMENTS AND ANY INFORMATION GIVEN IS PASSED TO THE DOCTOR TO HELP THEM TO TRIAGE THE PATIENTS IN GREATEST CLINICAL NEED FIRST. IN A HIGH NUMBER OF CASES PATIENTS DO NOT  NEED A FACE TO FACE CONSULTATION AND PROBLEMS CAN BE SORTED OVER THE TELEPHONE WHICH SAVES THE PATIENT A JOURNEY TO THE PRACTICE. IF THE TRIAGE DOCTOR FEELS YOU NEED TO BE SEEN BY A GP THEN AN APPOINTMENT WILL BE OFFERED EITHER FOR THAT DAY OR WHEN THE TRIAGE DOCTOR FEELS NECESSARY. WE WILL NEVER REFUSE YOU AN APPOINTMENT ON THE DAY OR IN ADVANCE BUT IT MAY NOT ALWAYS BE WITH THE GP OF YOUR CHOICE OR AT THE MOST CONVENIENT TIME TO YOU AS WE CAN ONLY WORK WITH THE GP'S AND TIMES WE HAVE AVAILABLE TO US WHEN YOU MAKE YOUR REQUEST.

            In addition to booked surgeries, we also offer OPEN SURGERY. This facility is offered on weekday mornings for those who have problems that are urgent or quick and cannot wait for a routine appointment.  If you arrive between 8.30 – 10.00am you will be seen by whichever doctor is holding open surgery that morning.  All patients attending the open surgery, including children, will be seen in order of arrival.  However, should a patient have an urgent medical need, they will be given priority.  Inevitably there will be times when this surgery is busy so please be prepared to wait.  Please do not abuse the open surgery: book an appointment if the problem is not urgent.  This surgery is not suitable for long term or on-going problems.  For these, or if you wish to see a particular doctor, you should make an appointment.CONSULTATION BY TELEPHONE Some problems can easily be resolved by discussion with a doctor over the telephone. To do this please telephone 01883 347811 before 10.30am. The doctor will then ring you back after their morning surgery.
Appointments to see both doctors and nurses can be booked up to 4 weeks in advance.
We also offer OUT OF HOURS APPOINTMENTS Tuesday and Friday mornings from 7.30am-8.00am and Tuesday evenings 6.30pm-7.30pm.

            Travel Advice
Planning a holiday? Before you travel ensure you are fully immunised

Are you possibly planning or have a trip abroad and are seeking travel health advice.  Aegis Medical Centre offers a travel advice service.

What you need to do?

We would first ask you to complete a travel risk assessment form so we can assess your risk, the recommended vaccines, any necessary malaria tablets (if you are travelling to a malarious region) and the advice most appropriate for your needs.

How do you do this? 

THIS FORM IS FOUND AT THE BOTTOM OF THE WEB PAGE AT THE NEXT ASSOCIATED DOCUMENTS. 

please complete the print out form and drop into the practice or you can collect a paper form from the surgery and return it.  Whichever way you choose this must be done before you are seen in an appointment.
Please also contact the surgery to book the initial appointment as early as possible, - 

THIS SHOULD BE AT LEAST SIX TO EIGHT WEEKS IN ADVANCE OF YOUR DEPARTURE DATE OR EVEN EARLIER IF POSSIBLE, as a second appointment will be required with the practice nurse to actually receive the vaccinations.  Some of the vaccinations have to be ordered in as they are not all a stock item. 

What will happen then?

You will be booked in to see Marion - Practice Nurse for a risk assessment consultation in which she will advise you on all aspects of travel advice, including any vaccines needed and/or malaria tablets required.

PLEASE BE AWARE THE AEGIS MEDICAL CENTRE DOES NOT PROVIDE PRIVATE TRAVEL VACCINES.

NHS travel vaccines will always be offered if you need them (these include hepatitis A, typhoid and diphtheria, tetanus, polio and sometimes cholera).  For more details on this please see NHS Choice (see below).

If you need a private travel vaccine, for example, yellow fever, rabies, Japanese encephalitis, then we will give you details of private travel clinics in the area that can provide this service.

Here are some resources to help you help us to provide you with the information required for travel abroad. It is always useful to do some personal research so you're more aware of your risks and advice available.

We also ask you to go to:
www.fitfortravel.nhs.uk/

Look up the destination you are travelling to, print off the information, read it and bring with you when you attend your appointment.

Travelling to a malarious area?

If you would like to learn more about the malaria drugs before your appointment which is always helpful, then useful information can be found on the A-Z index on the top navigation bar of www.fitfortravel.nhs.uk and go to the information sheet entitled ‘Malaria’ then click on the section entitled ‘Taking Antimalarial Tablets’ 

http://www.fitfortravel.nhs.uk/advice/malaria.aspx

Travelling to a high risk rabies area?

http://www.fitfortravel.nhs.uk/advice/disease-prevention-advice/rabies.aspx

Travelling to a yellow fever area?

http://www.fitfortravel.nhs.uk/advice/disease-prevention-advice/yellow-fever.aspx

Useful websites to visit before your appointment
NHS Choices		http://www.nhs.uk/Livewell/TravelHealth/Pages/Travelhealthhome.aspx
			http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Travel-immunisation/Pages/Introduction.aspx

Fit for Travel		http://www.fitfortravel.nhs.uk/home.aspx
National Travel Health Network and Centres (NaTHNaC)	 http://www.nathnac.org/travel/index.htm
Foreign and Commonwealth Office https://www.gov.uk/browse/abroad/travel-abroad

Total Number of GPS      -    2
If you require the means earnings of GPS  this is available in card copy form on request from the practice.
Last updated on 05 April 2016.

Appointments
All patients are seen by appointment. You may choose to see any doctor you wish.

This practice operates an advanced access system and you will be offered an appointment within two working days (same day appointments are always available if required). 

For this system to work smoothly we prefer to book doctors’ appointments no more than 48 hours in advance. If this is difficult please let us know and we will provide other options for you.

We also offer the opportunity to discuss your medical problem via telephone. Please mention this to the receptionist and we will arrange for a telephone consultation.
Alternatively we can call you back at the end of either morning or afternoon surgery.

Whilst we encourage our patients to consult us at the surgery whenever possible, home visits can be arranged for those housebound by illness or infirmity. Please telephone the surgery on 01564 739194 before 11.00 am if possible, or at any time in case of sudden severe illness.

We now offer online booking of some GP appointments - please contact reception for details

male:
Additional information
            Appointments
The practice operateson an appointment system in morning and evening. ( 10 min slot per patient)
Patients can attend in person or ring in between 8 am till 11 am to make an appointment. Four doctors available in the morning and 3 in the evening who speak Urdu, Bengali, English and Mirpuri. We have to female doctor who works Thursday and Friday mornings.
However if you want to see a particular doctor and that particular doctor is not available on that day, you are welcome to see any doctor on that and then make an appointment to see the doctor of your choice. 
Appointments for the nurses for diiferent clinics can be made by telephone 0121 328 1977 by comeing to the practice. Routine appointments may be made well in advance which will enable us to offer you an appointment at a time more suitable to your requirements.
Telephone Consultation
If you would like to have a telephone consultation, please leave your name, address, telephone number as well as the reason for the consultation in as much detail as possible with the reception staff. The doctor will ring you at the end of the surgery and assess the patients condition over the telephone. The results will likely be one of the following:

    Advice will be given over the phone eliminating the need for a face-to-face consultation. 
    Arrangements will be made fpr a prescription to be ready to collect from reception later on that day. 
    If it is considered urgent a face-to-face appointment for sometime that day will be arranged 


Home Visit
Patients are requested to telephone the surgery before 10am if a visit is required on that day.
Emergencey visits only will be arranged after that time.
Please give the reception staff as much information as possible to enable the doctor to allocate priority to house calls. Please remeber that several patients can be seen at the surgery in the time it takes to do on home visits and that clinical examination is best carried out at the surgeyr.
Please also note a home visit will be made if a doctor feels that you are not well after a telephone consultation. The final decision rests with the doctor.
Emergencey Appointments.
If you or your family member is suffering from a serious problem such as chest pain or sever bleeding call 999.
If you or member of your family are suffering with an illness that requie treatment the same day, please telephone the surgery and we will accomadate you.

Additional information
            We operate early morning GP and Practice Nurse appointments from 7:30am daily for patients who work.

**************************************************************************************************
Please note we close at 2.30pm on Wednesday afternoon for staff training.

**************************************************************************************************

Arranging an appointment.      When you contact the surgery either via phone or in person the following options are available and our receptionists will do their best to guide you to the most appropriate choice:

**********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

Same day telephone advice.      These surgeries run from 0830-1830 Monday-Friday. 
You will usually be put straight through to the on-call doctor but if they are unavailable the receptionists will inform you of this and take a number on which we can contact you. This option should be used if you need guidance regarding treatment or if you are unsure if you need an appointment. It is also useful if you think that investigations or treatment may be appropriate before you are seen by a doctor e.g. if you think that you may be anaemic it may be appropriate for us to arrange blood tests and then review you with the results of these.

**********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
 
Minor Illness Surgeries are available in the morning and afternoons.  The receptionist will guide you to one of these surgeries if appropriate. Please note that these are slightly shorter than routine appointments and the doctor will normally only be able to deal with the single problem that you have told the receptionist about. All the doctors do their best to run to time with these surgeries but due to on-call commitment some delays may be unavoidable.

 
**********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
Booked routine appointments.   For ongoing problems we urge you to arrange follow up with the same doctor as this will improve continuity and quality of care.    We release routine appointments in stages up to two weeks in advance and please book on of these appointments if there is a specific doctor that you wish to see.  
**************************************************************************************************

Additional information
            The Appointment System
We operate a flexible and responsive system for booking appointments with the doctor and nurse practitiioners.  We work hard to provide an excellent and accessible appointment system: Patient survey results show we are succeeding.  We are always looking for ways of improving the service further.
How it works

    Appointments can be booked in advance (usually up to 6 weeks for doctors and 6 months for nurse practitioners). 
    We offer same day appointments which can be booked on the day of request for either the doctor or the nurse practitioner. 
    If you would prefer, we can arrange  telephone consultation with either a GP or a nurse practitioner. Please contact reception to arrange this for you.
    We offer a daily minor illness clinic with our experienced nurse practitioner, who can also prescribe, for the following: 

Coughs/colds                                        Conjunctivitis
Earache                                                Chest infections
Diarrhoea and vomiting                        Minor injuries, e.g. cuts/burns, bites
Emergency contraception                    Cystitis / urine infections
Vaginal discharge                                Skin infections
Infected wounds/dressings

Appointments can be booked/cancelled using our On-Line facility.  This 24/7 service means that you can book your own appointment with the doctor/nurse or order your repeat medications using your own Internet connection.

Appointment- Advance access:

2013 Shingles Vaccine launch

The Department of Health have advised that they will begin offering the shingles vaccine on a phased introduction. At Maypole Health Centre, we understand this to mean that they will be introducing the vaccine to certain age groups between the ages of 70 and 79 yrs.

We anticipate its introduction to be around Autumn ( flu season) and so we would anticipate inviting those who will fall into this criteria in at the same time as they would usually expect to attend for their seasonal flu vaccine making it doubly important to watch out for the flu clinic dates. Please be advised, we will be unable to vaccinate patients who do not fall inot the age groups defined by the Department of Health.

 




Urgent appointment:
If you consider your condition to be urgent, please tell the
receptionist. 

Cancellation of appointment:
If you are unable to keep your appointment, please let the
receptionist know as soon as possible ( not 5 or 10 minutes before time) so that the appointment can be offered to another patient.


Home visit:
Telephone the surgery before 10:30 am if you cannot come
to the surgery. Please remember that a doctor should only 
be asked to make a home visit if the patient is too ill to 
be brought to the surgery.


Change of personal details:
If you change your name, address or telephone number or mobile number, 
please notify the surgery as soon as possible at time of booking your appointment.

Telephone Advice:
If you feel you need to seek a doctor’s advice by telephone,
please ring between 11:30 am and 12:15 pm.
Practice Nurse between 1200 pm and 1230pm

Enquiries and Test results
Telephone enquiries are best made at the end of morning 
surgery after 11:00 am or early afternoon 14:00 pm  when staff will have more time 
to help you.


Receptionists:
The receptionists are here to help you. They have a 
difficult job to do with phone calls and enquiries from 
all directions. When telephoning for medical attention,  
the receptionists may ask for a few details. They have been   
trained to make these enquiries in order to help you in 
the most appropriate way.

NHS 111 is the new three-digit telephone service that's being introduced to improve access to NHS urgent care services. Patients can use this number when they need medical help or advice and it's not urgent enough to call 999. NHS 111 operates 24/7, 365 days per year and is free to use from a landline and a mobile.

male:
Additional information
            Your Walk-in Centre has moved

Showell Park Walk-in Centre has moved from Friday 1st April 2016 to the new Urgent Care Centre, 1st floor, above the Emergency Department at New Cross Hospital.

The GP surgery will still be available at Showell Park Health Centre. In order to use this GP surgery you can register as a patient. Forms can be collected from the surgery reception or completed via this website. 

Walk in Centre services at the Phoenix Walk-in Centre, Parkfield Road, WV4 6ED will remain unchanged. They are available between 10am and 7pm Monday to Friday and 10am to 4pm on weekends and bank holidays.

Pharmacies, NHS111 or your GP are also available to offer advice.

Don’t forget that there are other healthcare options available instead of the Walk-in Centre or calling 999. Pharmacists can offer far more than just medicines. They can provide you with an on the day consultation to talk about your symptoms.

To improve access for all patients to your local GP practice it’s worth registering for Online Services. This allows patients to:

book appointments
request repeat prescriptions online
The receptionist at your practice can give you more information so you can get started. More information can be found on www.nhs.uk by typing Patient Online into the search box.

Patients should get the right care in the right place, the first time. Accessing the right care in the right place will usually result in reduced waiting times.

Please call NHS 111 or use NHS Choices for advice and guidance on where to access the right care for you.

male:
Additional information
            It is important to recognise that both Surgeries are extremely busy and the principle aim of the booking system is to ensure that patients can, and do, receive the support they need.  It is therefore necessary to operate a system which allocates appointments according to the level of need and urgency.


Contact with the both Surgeries can be made by phone, on-line or by visiting reception during normal surgery hours.  If you are phoning please state which surgery you prefer. The phones are particularly busy between 8am and 10am so please try and avoid these hours if you have a routine enquiry.  The on-line booking system is accessible 24h a day, 7 days a week and is an easy way to book routine appointments.  If you have not previously used the on –line booking system this may be arranged at reception (a consent form must be completed to enable the surgery to generate your login details).

There are a number of different ways of obtaining the help and support you need from the surgery:

•Routine appointments with all doctors may be booked 2 weeks in advance and the appointments are 10 minutes in length.  If you wish to cover several medical problems you may be asked to make a follow up appointment.

•Emergency appointments may be booked on the day.  These are 5 minute appointment and are appropriate for any medical problem which cannot wait for the next routine appointment and may be booked at either surgery. They may be used for problems such as infections as well as more serious complaints. Typically, in the time available, only one medical problem can be covered in these appointments. If all the emergency appointments have all been taken when you request an appointment the doctor will telephone you.  In some cases it may be possible to give telephone advice, arrange a prescription or offer an appointment on another day.  If however, as a result of the telephone consultation, it is felt that you (or your child) should be seen by the doctor an emergency appointment will still be made available on the same day.

•Home Visits. For those people who cannot visit the surgery for an appointment because they are too ill to attend or housebound, a Home Visit can be arranged.  Please phone before 10am to request a visit.  The doctor may phone you back before visiting.
 
•Telephone consultations can also be requested if you consider that it is not necessary, or not possible, to see the doctor in person. These are booked through the receptionist who will make the necessary arrangements.

•Practice Nurse/Nurse Practitioner.  It is not always necessary to see a doctor.  A number of consultations such as for contraception, cervical smears, well person checks, travel advice and dressings can be dealt with by the Practice Nurse or Nurse Practitioner. Please ensure that appointments for travel advice are made in good time – ideally at least 8 weeks prior to your date of departure. 

•Medication reviews – If a medication review is due please make a routine appointment with the doctor.  In some circumstances the review may be carried out by the practice nurse (e.g. Raised blood pressure, asthma, Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease or contraception reviews) or by the Nurse Practitioner (e.g. Diabetes checks).  The receptionist or your doctor will be able to guide you as to which professional would be most appropriate.  In the event that the Surgery is not able to see you before your medication is due to run out they can arrange an interim prescription to cover you until you can be seen.

The Surgery recognises that there is considerable pressure on the appointment system.  If you are having difficulty making an appointment with the doctor of your choice or on the day of your choice the receptionists will endeavour to offer you an alternative or to advise you when an appointment may become available.  The Surgery review the appointment system regularly and welcome your feedback or ideas.  There is a comment box in each surgery.

Help the Surgery to help you!

•Seek self-help remedies where possible.  Discuss over-the-counter treatments with your local pharmacist.
•Be flexible about when you can attend and who you will see.
•Be organised about booking reviews in plenty of time and don’t wait until you have run out of medication before contacting the surgery.
•Only book an emergency appointment if you absolutely cannot wait until the next routine appointment.
•Only request a Home Visit if there is no way you can attend the surgery.

male:
Additional information
            Appointments
We are constantly monitoring and reviewing our appointment access.
We have a same day appointment/advice system. Call between 8.00am-1.00pm , give your request to the receptionist who will take the details regarding the problem and what outcome you would like, such as an appointment, referral, prescription etc.The receptionist will pass the details to our doctors to triage and give appropriate treatment and care required. A member of the Same Day Care Team (Dr, Nurse or receptionist) will then call you back and feedback to you what action the Dr has requested, such as offer an appointment, a tel consultation, referral, sicknote or prescription etc.

The aim of this system is to improve patient experience and access. We also hope to see less demand placed on the service at 8.00am with patients trying to get through early  as we promise to deal with all same day requests that day if received by 1,00pm. The earlier we get the request the quicker we will be able to access the patients needs and address them but there is no longer the need for the rush first thing in the morning due to appointments be allocated by the Dr through a triage service throughout the day.

We book appointments 2 weeks in advance but  do understand at the moment there is a wait for a routine appointment.

Additional information
            The doctors share in the day-to-day workload.  We open at 0820 and surgeries start at 0830 each day.  We provide a split between Emergency, 48 hours doctor appointments and routine pre-bookable appointments.  

Routine appointments are for non urgent matters and made available with your usual GP up to one month in advance.  If your GP wishes you to come back for a follow up appointment, they will issue you with a slip asking reception to book you an appointment.

48 Hour Doctor appointments are avaialble if you cannot wait for your usual GP (though not the doctor of your choice) that can be booked 48 hours in advance.

Emergency Appointments are for urgent matters that have to be dealt with that day.  You will be given an appointment with our Nurse Practitioner who can diagnose and treat most common illnesses.

            We are open, across the practice, from 8.30am to 6.30pm every day, Monday to Friday. In addition we have extended access surgeries from 6.30pm -8.30pm at Ancaster on Tuesdays. We have set, 10 minute, appointments for the doctor on the times listed above in Surgery Opening Times which you can book at reception, over the telephone or on our Systmonline service (https://systmonline.tpp-uk.com/login). If you need to be seen urgently, we shall do our best to allocate you with an emergency appointment. Alternatively, our duty doctor will call you back for a telephone consultation after the morning or afternoon surgery is finished depending on what time you call. If you are too ill to travel to the surgery and wish either a home visit or to speak with the doctor, please try to telephone with your request before 10.00am. The doctor will then organise a visit or telephone you after the morning surgery.

male:
Additional information
            How does it work?

111 will connect the caller to a team located in Peterborough of fully trained call advisers, who are supported by experienced nurses and paramedics. They will ask the caller questions to assess the symptoms, and give them the healthcare advice they need or direct the most appropriate and available local service.

Where possible, the NHS 111 team will book you an appointment or transfer you directly to the people you need to speak to. If NHS 111 advisers think you need an ambulance they will arrange for one to be sent to you.

People living in the Cambridgeshire and Peterborough area should continue to call their GP for non-urgent medical advice. 

The 111 service is being provided by Herts Urgent Care, an organisation that has a proven track record in providing the 111 service elsewhere.

Calls to 111 are recorded. All calls and the records created are maintained securely, and will only be shared with others directly involved with your care.

            We do close once a month on a Tuesday lunchtime between 12 noon and 1pm. The telephone messaging service gives details of how to contact a GP in an emergency if you are unable to wait for the surgery to re-open. This hour is used for the GP's, Practice Nurses and Admin Team to receive educational training. We do invite speakers in to give talks and presentations. We have met with Healthwatch, Osteoarthritis Speaker, CPR, (resuscitation) and use of the defibrillator, we invited The Memory Clinic to speak with the Doctors and Nurses, they discussed screening and diagnosis of dementia patients, drug management of dementia patients and the complications of prescribing it. The Admin Team did their own Dementia Awareness Training with the Manager/RGN of a local Nursing Home specialising in Dementia Care. All Admin staff are now "Dementia Friends". Three times a year we close for a whole afternoon, this is so the whole practice can receive educational training on a larger scale.This training maybe on site or off site. This is in line with all Shrewsbury Practices. Contact details for emergency contacts are on the telephone messaging service.

Additional information
             WE ARE A RESEARCH ACTIVE PRACTICE:
We have recently been accredited by the Royal College of General Practitioners (RCGP), as ‘Research Ready’ so we are able to participate in research studies that CliniclResearch Network (CRN) offers to benefit the wider community in the long term.

To become research ready the practice has completed an online self-accreditation questionnaire which covers the minimum requirements of The Research Governance Framework for Health and Social Care, Department of Health (2005). The accreditation has been developed by the Royal College of General Practitioners in conjunction with the National Institute of Health Research (NIHR) and the CRN. 

The Clinical Research Network East of England (CRN EoE) is one of a family of national research networks working together with the Comprehensive Local Research Networks to provide a wide range of support to the local research community. Our Practice participates in research activity and works closely with the CRN EoE, creating more opportunities for more patients to be involved in research should they wish. 

No studies are compulsory and patients may decline any invitation to join a study.

More details can be found at: http://www.nihr.ac.uk/

accepting: We are currently accepting new patients
male:
Additional information
            Drop-in Surgeries
 
We offer a drop-in surgery every morning from 9.00am – 10.30am.  This is for patients who feel they need to see a doctor the same day. Patients are seen in turn and should appreciate that there may be patients with appointments who will be seen before them. 
 
Please note – Emergencies Take Priority at All Times
 
Patients attending drop-in surgery must be present when their name is called or they will lose their place and be put at the back of the queue.  We therefore encourage patients to stay in the waiting room, once they are on the list, because it is difficult to predict the time at which they will be called.  
 
It is not possible to reserve a place in the drop-in surgery by telephone, or by calling at the surgery the previous day. Also, it is not possible to request to see a particular doctor at drop-in surgery.
 
Drop-in surgery is ideal if:
 
    -  your illness has developed or deteriorated very recently
    -  you are concerned that your condition should not wait until the next routine appointment.
 
However, drop-in surgery can be quite busy, and there is often a wait to be seen.  Because of this, the drop-in in not really appropriate for:
 
      - obtaining repeat prescriptions or results of tests
      - dealing with multiple problems
      - dealing with problems which have been present for some time
      - routine follow-up of chronic problems
 
If in doubt, please check with the receptionist

Additional information
            Urgent Appointments and Calls

Urgent appointments are for people who are feeling unwell, distressed or in pain and need to see a doctor or nurse on the same day.

Duty Doctor

If you have an urgent health problem, you will always be able to speak to the emergency Duty Doctor on the same day. Once the receptionist has taken some brief details, the doctor will call you back and give you advice or arrange an emergency clinic appointment for you if this is necessary.

Express Clinic

The receptionist may offer you an appointment in our Express Clinic, where you will be assessed by one of our nurse practitioners. The nurse practitioners are able to assess and treat a range of common health problems and can prescribe medications if required. They are also trained to spot signs of more serious illness, so they can alert the supervising doctor.

            Evenings and Weekends.  We are able to offer appointments Monday to Friday 6 pm to 8 pm, Saturday and Sunday 9am to 12 noon.

Appointments will be delivered at one of the five surgeries listed below on a rota basis and will be 15 minutes long. If the appointment is not with your own surgery, at the time of booking the appointment you will need to provide verbal authority for the clinician providing your care to access your medical notes.  It is important to note that the receptionist is unable to book the appointment without this consent.

To make an appointment please phone Reception during normal surgery hours (08:30-18:30 Mon - Fri excluding Bank Holidays).  

 If you have an urgent medical problem after 18:30 or on a Saturday you should continue to contact the Out of Hours service by dialling 111.

Our phone lines will still close at 18:30 and will not be open on a Saturday morning.  If you need to make a late cancellation you can contact reception by email:  receptionists.longfurlong@nhs.uk

Additional information
            SAME DAY ACCESS

Patients who request to see a doctor the same day will have to speak to their usual GP /nurse first to check on your symptoms.  You will be asked by the receptionist to leave a contact number and brief details and then be advised by the receptionist when a doctor will call you back to discuss your problem. 

THE DOCTOR  WILL DECIDE IF YOU NEED TO BE SEEN THAT DAY OR IF IT WILL WAIT FOR THE NEXT ROUTINE APPOINTMENT.

We would like to remind patients that the same day appointments are for urgent medical problems only.

Patients will not be seen for the following conditions:

    - Repeat Prescriptions
    - Sick notes
    - Long Standing Conditions
    - Test Results (unless instructed by GP)                        
    
We would ask that all request are made before 11.00am.

male:
Additional information
            Appointments can be booked by telephone, in person at the reception desk or via the internet.  If choosing the internet facility, you will need to pop into surgery with ID where an account will be set up for you there and then.  The practice provides both face to face appointments and telephone consultations. 

We ask that requests for home visits are made before 10.30am which will allow the visiting Doctor time between the morning and afternoon surgery. 

Please note that appointments with the doctor are for 10 minutes only. If you need to see one of the clinical team for numerous things, please explain this at the time of booking your appointment so the correct amount of time can be allocated for you.  

Routine chronic disease monitoring such as blood pressure, blood tests, diabetes, heart disease, asthma and COPD checks are done by our practice nursing team.

Minor ailments such as coughs, colds, sore throats, minor rashes, etc can be dealt with by a pharmacist. 

If the doctor has asked you to see him/her about test results or hospital correspondence please check the results are back before you make your appointment.

If you are unable to make it in for your appointment please let us know so we can use the time to see someone else. 

Our policy is that we do not see patients if they are more than 10 minutes late for their appointment as it will disrupt the appointment times for other patients.
 
When the Surgery is Closed

In possible life-threatening situations dial 999 for an emergency ambulance. For other urgent problems that really cannot wait until the next routine surgery please telephone NHS Direct on 111 for advice or telephone the surgery.  If you telephone the surgery "out of hours" you will be given the telephone number for the Out of Hours Primary Care Centre (run by Go To Doc).  

The Accident and Emergency Department should only be attended in the event of life threatening emergencies. Walk in Clinics can treat other less serious conditions and some pharmacies run Minor Ailment Clinics.

accepting: We are currently accepting new patients
male:
Additional information
            OUT OF HOURS SERVICE.

The surgery is closed on Saturdays, Sundays and Bank Holidays.  

Emergencies when the surgery is closed are dealt with by the Out of Hours Service.  The telephone number for the Out of Hours Service is 111.   Please note, you should consider whether your call is for an emergency or whether it can wait until the surgery re-opens.

PLT AFTERNOON CLOSURES

The Practice is closed, usually BUT NOT ALWAYS on the last Thursday of every month from 1pm for Protected Learning Time.  During this time the practice is covered by the Out of Hours Service and again before contacting the Out of Hours Service, you should consider whether your call can wait until the surgery re-opens at 8am the next morning.

We have extended hours on a Monday, Tuesday and Thursday evening from 6.30pm - 7pm.  These appointments are pre-bookable only.

Pre bookable, evening and weekend GP appointments to suit you

There are a wide range of GP appointments available to fit into your lifestyle. 

Pre-bookable evening and weekend appointments with a local GP are available from 6pm-8pm Monday-Friday, 8am-4pm Saturdays and Sundays 10-2pm at Bath Street Health and Wellbeing Centre. 

Easily accessible, the Health and Wellbeing Centre is in the town centre and accessible by public transport on the town’s main bus routes.

To access an extended access appointment, please call us and we will arrange the appointment for you. 

Please be aware that you will need to consent to share your medical record with the GP who is on call in the Extended Access Service. 

If need to see a GP when we are closed, please call NHS 111 for our out of hours service.

Additional information
            EXTENDED APPOINTMENT ACCESS PROVIDED BY WIGAN FEDERATIONS WORKING TOGETHER 

The Wigan GP Extended Hours now offer appointments with Nurses for a variety of services and reviews between 18.30pm and 20.00pm weekdays and between 10.00am and 4.00pm on Saturdays. To get an appointment during these times, Wigan Patients can ring 01942 482848.

Appointments with the Nurse are for:- Smears, Contraception pill checks (not depo provera injections), Long term conditions, COPD Reviews, Asthma Reviews, Diabetic Reviews (bloods to be done a few days before the review), Peripheral Arterial Disease Reviews, Ischaemic Heart disease Reviews (bloods to be done a few days before), Stroke Reviews, Atrial Fibrillation Reviews, Heart Failure Reviews.

            GP Care Wakefield - additional appointments available
The  main telephone line  01977 703635 opens at 8.00am until 6pm( except when closed for training) Monday to Friday, after which calls are diverted automatically to GP Care Wakefield who offer appointments as follows:- 6 – 10 pm Monday to Friday, and 9 – 3pm Saturday’s, Sunday’s and Bank Holidays. In addition to the above, during 6pm & 8pm Monday to Friday, and 9am & 1pm on Saturday’s, Sunday’s and Bank Holiday’s, patients can be seen for routine nurse care. You can call 111 when you need medical help fast but it’s not a 999 emergency. NHS 111 is a fast and easy way to get the right help, whatever the time. 
NHS 111 is available 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. Calls are free from landlines and mobile phones. 

When to use it
You should use the NHS 111 service if you urgently need medical help or advice but it's not a life-threatening situation.

Call 111 if:

you need medical help fast but it's not a 999 emergency 
you think you need to go to A&E or need another NHS urgent care service 
you don't know who to call or you don't have a GP to call 
you need health information or reassurance about what to do next 

Minor illnesses can attend the Walk-In-Centre: 47 King Street, Wakefield. 

8am - 8pm 7 days a week.

Additional information
            Medicals and Reports
For insurance reports, driving, fitness to travel, letters etc, please speak to our reception staff for details and/or to arrange an appointment. These are not part of General Medical Services and therefore incur a charge.  The website has an up to date list of charges.
Complaints / Suggestions / Feedback
If you have a suggestion, wish to provide feedback or make a complaint about any aspect of our service, please let us know by writing to the Practice Manager.  Full details of our complaints procedure are available in the surgery or the surgery website.
Data Protection
Under the Data Protection Act we require a patient’s written permission before we can discuss their care  or treatment with family members, guardians, carers  or friends. This also applies to patients aged 12-16.          
        Clinical Standards of Care – Patients Charter
As a patient you have the right to receive a safe high standard of medical care and to be treated with dignity and respect.  Our practice staff are here to help to look after your medical needs and are trained to be aware of vulnerable patients and those with special needs.  Please treat our staff with the same courtesy and respect you would expect to receive from them.  If you wish to speak to the receptionist please ask to see them privately. Chaperones are available to any patient when seeing a doctor or nurse.
Care Data 
Information about you and the care you receive is shared, in a secure system, by healthcare staff to support your treatment and care.  You have a choice. If you are happy for your information to be used in this way you do not have to do anything. If you have any concerns please speak to our reception team. Further information is available on the surgery website.
Patient Participation Group
Patients are welcome to join the group to help in developing and providing feedback to the practice and CCG in future services and developments for the local area.  Further information is available on the surgery website.
Medical Records
Our staff are trained in accordance with the Data Protection Act and all the staff contracts include a clause that any breaches of confidentiality may result in dismissal. You have the right to request access to your full medical records.  A standard fee is chargeable for copies of your records.  All requests must be put in writing to the practice.  
Please make sure you advise the surgery of any address or telephone number changes as soon as possible.

Additional information
            Walk in Service

There is a walk-in service at Park Community Practice, Horne Street, Halifax, HX1 5UA that is open from 08:00 to 18:00 weekends and Bank Holidays.

All patients are welcome to use this service for minor illness or urgent care that does not warrant an A&E attendance. Examples of things that you could attend for are: emergency family planning, coughs, colds and flu-like symptoms, minor cuts and wounds, dressings, muscle and joint injuries, skin complaints, sunburn,  stomach ache, indigestion, vomiting, diarrhoea. 

If you attend the walk-in centre we will be notified so that we can ensure that your medical record is kept fully up to date.

Accident & Emergency (A&E)

A&E departments assess and treat patients with serious injuries or illnesses. Generally, you should visit A&E or call 999 for emergencies, such as:
•	loss of consciousness, 
•	pain that is not relieved by simple analgesia,
•	acute confused state,
•	severe chest pain, or
•	breathing difficulties.
If you are unsure then please feel free to ring the practice for advice.
 
Call 999 in an emergency. Chest pains and / or shortness of breath constitute an emergency.

male:
Additional information
            The NHS 111 service is staffed by a team of fully trained advisers, supported by experienced nurses. They will ask you questions to assess your symptoms, then give you the healthcare advice you need or direct you straightaway to the local service that can help you best. That could be A&E, an out of hours doctor, a walk in centre, a community nurse, an emergency dentist or a late-opening chemist.

Where possible, the NHS 111 team will book you an appointment or transfer you directly to the people you need to speak to. If you need an ambulance, one will be sent just as quickly as if you had dialled 999.

If a health professional has given you a specific phone number to call when you are concerned about your condition, continue to use that number.

If you have difficulties communicating or hearing, you can use the NHS 111 service through a textphone by calling 18001 111.

Patients who are not well enough to travel will be visited at home by a duty doctor who may not be a member of this practice but will always be a qualified GP from the local area.

All calls are recorded.

male:
Additional information
            The NHS 111 service is staffed by a team of fully trained advisers, supported by experienced nurses. They will ask you questions to assess your symptoms, then give you the healthcare advice you need or direct you straightaway to the local service that can help you best. That could be A&E, an out of hours doctor, a walk in centre, a community nurse, an emergency dentist or a late-opening chemist. 
Where possible, the NHS 111 team will book you an appointment or transfer you directly to the people you need to speak to. If you need an ambulance, one will be sent just as quickly as if you had dialled 999.
If a health professional has given you a specific phone number to call when you are concerned about your condition, continue to use that number.
If you have difficulties communicating or hearing, you can use the NHS 111 service through a textphone by calling 18001 111.
Patients who are not well enough to travel will be visited at home by a duty doctor who may not be a member of this practice but will always be a qualified GP from the local area.
All calls are recorded.

accepting: We are currently accepting new patients
male:
Additional information
            From 16th October 2017 following consultation with our PPG, we changed our appointment system to a more traditional face to face system. Face to face doctor appointments for the same day, the next day, two days time and a week ahead are released every weekday morning at 8am when the telephone lines open. We have a number of appointments that are also available to book online using the patient access system. Previously we have asked patients to call back at 12.30 for an afternoon appointment, this is no longer necessary as all appointments for the whole day are released at 8am. We offer a small number of telephone consultations these are useful  for followup calls after test results or where a face to face appointment is not required. Nurse and Phlebotomy appointments can be booked 4-6 weeks in advance.
We have  a number of commuter surgeries (early morning and evening clinics) and Saturday morning clinics for pre-bookable telephone appointments. Ask at Reception for more details about these clinics.We also offer a same day 'Sit and Wait' clinic, this is a walk in clinic for patients with new medical problems (no longer than 2 weeks old), the clinic is open for patients to check in at reception between 9am and 12.30pm. Patients are guaranteed to be seen by the doctor on duty the same day, however we cannot guarantee waiting times. Our Advanced Nurse Practitioners provide telephone call backs for patients. They can advise over the telephone and where necessary arrange an appointment in surgery. Our receptionists will advise you regarding the most appropriate clinician for you to see/speak to when you call in or visit the reception desk.

Additional information
            Extended Access to Primary Care:

From 12 June 2017, this practice is taking part in the GP extended access service at Westbourne Green Community Healthcare Centre.

This means that you may be offered an opportunity to attend an evening (after 6.30 pm) or weekend appointment at Westbourne Green to see a health care professional  or to take part in other activities that will improve your health and wellbeing.

The service is run by Bradford Care Alliance, which represents most GP practices in the Bradford area.  Medical appointments are with GPs and other healthcare staff who work in the area; therefore, your appointment may not be with a clinician from this practice.

To use the service we will ask for your consent to share your medical record with the extended access service.  When you are offered an appointment, our receptionists will talk to you about what this means and why it is necessary.

•	You can read more about the extended hours service here
•	Westbourne Green Community Healthcare Centre is located at 26 Heaton Road, Bradford BD8 8RA

Additional information
            ALTERNATIVE HEALTH CARE SPECIALISTS

Minor injuries can also be dealt with at Minor Injuries Unit (MIU) at 
Gravesend & North Kent Hospital, Bath Street, Gravesend open 09:00 – 21:00 seven days a week or at, 
Sevenoaks Hospital, open 08:00 – 20:00 (x-ray from 09:00 – 16:00 only) these are both Emergency Nurse Practitioner (ENP) led clinics. The ENPs are trained in assessing and diagnosing a wide range of minor injuries; i.e. cuts and bruises, strains and sprains, foreign bodies in eyes, minor burns and scalds.  Major accidents, injuries and illnesses should attend Darent Valley Hospital A&E.
NHS 111 is a new triaging service replacing NHS Direct.  Patients should telephone 111 where they will be directed to the most appropriate service.  Emergency only cases should still call 999.

            We now offer extended hours during the following times:

Monday morning from 7.30am

Monday evening

Saturday morning from 08.00am

The surgery will only provide limited services such as pre-booked appointments rather than offering the full range of services available during its "normal" opening hours.
The "Extended Opening Hours" surgeries are intended for patients who are not in a position to attend during the practice’s normal 8:30 am to 5:30 pm Monday to Friday surgeries

They are solely and exclusively for pre-booked appointments

There will be a limited number of Doctors and Nurses conducting Extended Hours surgery and no additional clinicians on site

"Extended Opening Hours" surgeries will have a limited number of clinicians on a rota basis, meaning that there may be only one doctor and one Nurse seeing patients each week.

This means that your own doctor might only be in a position to offer "Extended Opening Hours" appointments once every few weeks.

Normal weekend or night-time Out of Hours arrangements will apply for acute or same day problems

The surgery will not be open to deal with acute or "same day" problems such as sudden illnesses, exacerbations of existing problems or accidents during its "Extended Opening Hours". The Telephones will not be open to book appointments or make enquiries.

Patients will still have to contact the Out of Hours service for immediately necessary medical advice and treatment.

male:
Additional information
            Registering as a Patient: You can register as a patient at Southgate Medical Group ONLY if you live in Southgate & your family in the same home are already registered with us.  Otherwise, our list is capped as per details at the top of this page.

If for any reason you are unable to attend any appointment please cancel your appointment by calling our Appointment Cancellation Line on 01293 536281. This is an answer service which asks you to leave specific details about the appointment you wish to cancel:

Appointment Cancellation Line
To save you both time and money trying to call the Surgery on the main number, there is a dedicated Appointment Cancellation Line

THE TELEPHONE NUMBER IS 01293 536281

This number is an answer machine service where you will be prompted to leave your Name, your Date of Birth, the Date and Time of Appointment you wish to cancel and the Name of the Doctor or Nurse you were booked to see.

Your appointment will then be cancelled by a member of our staff and free's up an appointment for another patient.

Named GP
 
As part of the NHS commitment to providing more personalised care, from June 2015 all practices are required to provide all their Patients with a named GP who will have overall responsibility for the care and support that our surgery provides.
 
•This will not impact your experience at the practice, the provision of appointments, your treatment, or which GP you can see.
•You may wonder why your allocated GP is not necessarily the one you see most regularly.  Please be assured that you can still access all of our medical team in exactly the same way as before.
•Having a named GP does not guarantee you will always be seen by that GP.
•If you wish to be registered with a different GP we can alter this for you. However, this does not change the availability of appointments for that GP.
•Please note that the GP responsible for your care may be subject to change and reallocation in the future
You do not need to take any further action, but if you have any questions or wish to know your named GP, please speak to Reception.
 
What does 'accountable' mean?
This is largely a role of oversight, with the requirements being introduced to reassure patients that they have one GP within the practice who is responsible for ensuring that this work is carried out on their behalf.  

What are the named GP's responsibilities to 75s and over?
This is unchanged from 2014-2015; for patients aged 75 and over the named accountable GP is responsible for:
 
• working with relevant associated health and social care professionals to deliver a multi-disciplinary care package that meets the needs of the patient
•ensuring that these patients have access to a health check as set out in section 7.9 of the GMS Contract Regulations.
 Does the requirement mean 24-hour responsibility for patients?
No. The named GP will not:
 
•take on vicarious responsibility for the work of other doctors or health professional
•take on 24-hour responsibility for the patient, or have to change their working hours. The requirement does not imply personal availability for GPs throughout the working wee
•be the only GP or clinician who will provide care to that patient

Can patients choose their own named GP
In the first instance, patients should simply be allocated a named GP. However, if a patient requests a particular GP, reasonable efforts should be made to accommodate their preference, recognising that there are occasions when the practice may not feel the patient's preference is suitable.

Do patients have to see the named GP when they book an appointment with the practice?
No. Patients can and should feel free to choose to see any GP or nurse in the practice in line with current arrangements. However, some practices may see this change as a way to encourage and promote a greater degree of continuity of care for patients.

NHS 111 is a new service that is being introduced to make it easier for you to access local NHS healthcare services. You can now call 111 when you need medical help fast, but is it not a 999 emergency.
NHS 111 is available 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. Calls are free from landlines and mobiles.
If you call the old Out of Hours number and wait for your call to be redirected, then call charges will occur. If you dial 111 directly, your call will be free.

male:
Additional information
            Where possible the Doctors prefer to see patients by appointment.  Appointments can be made through Reception or online through the electronic appointment booking facility.  

We also operate non-appointment (walk-in) surgeries every weekday morning.  These surgeries are for problems that cannot reasonably wait for the next available booked appointment and are for 5 minutes per consultation.  You must register in person or online at Horsmonden or Brenchley by 9.30am and you will be given an approximate time to see the Doctor.  Friday afternoon emergency "on the day" appointments are available by contacting Reception. Our Receptionists will take your details and the Duty Doctor will suggest the best course of action, which may include a telephone consultation, requesting that you attend a walk-in surgery or a regular consultation the following week or offering you an appointment at the Friday afternoon emergency session. Please telephone as early as possible on the day to request an appointment. 

Extended hours appointments with the Doctor or Practice Nurse are available for patients who cannot get to the surgery during normal opening times.  These appointments can only be booked through Reception and not through the electronic booking service.   Horsmonden Surgery - Monday 18:30 to 19:15 with the Doctor;  Horsmonden Surgery - Monday 18:30 to 19:00 with the Practice Nurse; Brenchley Surgery - Wednesday 18:30 to 19:00 with the Doctor.

Please note that calls after 1pm on Tuesdays will be redirected to Lamberhurst Surgery who will be able to deal with emergencies. For general enquiries, appointment booking or test results please contact Reception during normal reception opening times.

OUT OF HOURS — WHO TO CONTACT 
Alternative GP services for problems that won’t wait 
until we re-open are: 
A weekend walk in service is provided at the Boscombe and Springbourne Health Centre, Palmerston Road, 
Boscombe from 8am-8pm Saturdays and Sundays only. 
 If you are unwell at any time when the surgery is closed, you should ring NHS111 on the  following number.  1-1-1
 This number connects you to the call centre at St Leonards and your details will be taken and passed to a doctor or nurse who will ring you back and decide the most appropriate form of help.   Depending on the severity of your problem you may:
     · Receive advice over the telephone
· Be asked to visit the local treatment centre 
· Receive a visit from a doctor, paramedic, nurse or emergency care practitioner.
 Please note this service is for urgent medical problems only.  It is not for routine enquiries such as repeat prescriptions, booking appointments or test results. 
               Call 999  only if you are severely ill or if you have had a serious accident.
